## 1. One-Line Summary

* The Hook: An ultra-budget, highly tacky entry point into Chinese-style rubbers that offers phenomenal spin and short-game control at a virtually unbeatable price.
* Archetype: Budget Tacky All-Rounder / Beginner Forehand Looper.

---

## 2. Performance Analysis

* Speed & Gears
    * Passive Block Speed: Very low. The dead sponge absorbs pace, requiring you to actively push the ball over the net.
    * Active Loop Speed: Medium. It requires a full-body stroke to generate pace; the rubber will not do the work for you.
    * Linearity vs. Trampoline: Extremely linear. There is absolutely zero trampoline effect. What you put in is exactly what you get out.
    * Mid-Distance Carry: Poor. The lack of built-in catapult means the ball will often drop into the net if you retreat past mid-distance without massive physical effort.

* Spin Generation
    * Top-End Spin: High. If you have good brushing technique, the tacky topsheet grips the plastic ball aggressively.
    * Opening Loop: Exceptional. The tackiness makes lifting heavy backspin extremely safe and highly spinny, producing a very high arc.
    * Serve Quality: Excellent. You can generate massive backspin and sidespin on serves with minimal effort due to the sticky surface.

* Control & Short Game
    * Touch Play: Superb. The dead nature of the MOXA sponge allows for double-bouncing drop shots and incredibly tight pushes.
    * Spin Sensitivity: High. Because it is tacky, it reacts strongly to incoming spin, requiring precise bat angles on receive.
    * Flick Window: Forgiving but demands effort. You cannot rely on sponge-bounce to flick; you must actively brush over the ball.

* Throw Angle (Arc)
    * Trajectory: Medium-high.
    * Arc Behavior: Pronounced dip. The ball clears the net safely and dives aggressively onto the table due to the heavy topspin.

* Spin-Interaction Behavior
    * Against Heavy Topspin: Good, but requires an active block or counter-topspin. Passive blocking may lead to the ball popping up.
    * Against Heavy Backspin: Incredible. Lifting chops and pushes is where this rubber truly shines.
    * Error Pattern: Missing into the net when out of position, simply because the sponge provides no bailout speed.

