## 3. Technique-by-Technique Breakdown

* Serve
    * Elite-level grip for ghost serves and heavy backspin. It feels like cheating for a rubber at this price point.

* Receive
    * Push/Stop: Fantastic. You can kill the spin and drop the ball short with immense ease.
    * Flick/Flip: Requires a dedicated, active brush. Flat flicks will find the net.
    * Chiquita/Banana: Possible, but lacks the catapult needed to make it a lethal, fast weapon. It will be a slow, spinny Chiquita.

* Loop/Drive
    * First Loop (3rd Ball): Its absolute best offensive stroke. Highly reliable for starting the attack.
    * Continuous Looping: Tiring. The lack of catapult means you have to use maximum effort on every single swing.
    * Power Loop / Kill: Average. It lacks the top-end speed of ESN tensors or boosted DHS Hurricane 3. It will top out early.

* Countering
    * Counter-Topspin: Decent, but the sponge isn't quite dense enough in the softer versions to prevent bottoming out against extreme power.
    * Punch Counter / Active Block: Poor. Flat hitting and punching are not this rubber's strong suits due to the tacky topsheet.

* Blocking
    * Passive Block: Very stable but slow. You must close the angle well to handle incoming spin.
    * Active Block: Better. Adding a little push or forward motion helps return the ball with depth.

* Smash & Flat Hit
    * Below average. The sticky topsheet catches the ball and slows it down. Smashes feel mushy and lack final penetrative speed.

* Defense (If Relevant)
    * Chop: Surprisingly good. Many classic defenders use it on the forehand for heavy backspin chops due to its slow speed and high grip.
    * Lob/Fish: Difficult. Requires huge upward swings to get the ball deep onto the opponent's side.

